<heading bold="true" box="[151,435,1321,1347]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,435,1321,1347]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
<taxonomicName authority="Baird, 1843" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[151,431,1321,1347]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Acroperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1321,1347]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Acroperus</emphasis>
Baird, 1843
</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1391,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,649,1391,1416]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Parthenogenetic female short description.</emphasis>
Body oval, of variable height, head and valves with well-defined keel (
<figureCitation box="[159,254,1428,1453]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. A – D" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[200,1371,223,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[193,1389,223,1883]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. A – D, Acroperus africanus Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2015. A, lateral view. B, posteroventral corner of valves. C, postabdomen. D, antenna. E, Acroperus harpae (Baird, 1834), antenna. F – I, Alona affinis (Leydig, 1860) s. lato. F, lateral view. G, head pores. H, postabdomen. I, IDL and ODL of limb I. J – M. Alona kotovi Sinev, 2012. J, lateral view. K, head pores. L, postabdomen. M, IDL and ODL of limb I. (A – D, F – I—orig.; E—from Sinev (2009 b); J – M—from Sinev (2012 ))" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). Sculpture of valves as longitudinal lines. Posteroventral angle of valves with several small, closely spaced denticles (
<figureCitation box="[356,448,1463,1488]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. A – D" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[200,1371,223,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[193,1389,223,1883]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. A – D, Acroperus africanus Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2015. A, lateral view. B, posteroventral corner of valves. C, postabdomen. D, antenna. E, Acroperus harpae (Baird, 1834), antenna. F – I, Alona affinis (Leydig, 1860) s. lato. F, lateral view. G, head pores. H, postabdomen. I, IDL and ODL of limb I. J – M. Alona kotovi Sinev, 2012. J, lateral view. K, head pores. L, postabdomen. M, IDL and ODL of limb I. (A – D, F – I—orig.; E—from Sinev (2009 b); J – M—from Sinev (2012 ))" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). Rostrum triangular in lateral view, with pointed apex. Three main head pores with narrow connection between them, located at widened part of head keel. Lateral head pores minute. Labral keel of moderate width, with rounded apex, without clusters of setulae on posterior margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="457" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1391,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
Postabdomen long and narrow (
<figureCitation box="[563,652,1572,1597]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. A – D" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[200,1371,223,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[193,1389,223,1883]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. A – D, Acroperus africanus Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2015. A, lateral view. B, posteroventral corner of valves. C, postabdomen. D, antenna. E, Acroperus harpae (Baird, 1834), antenna. F – I, Alona affinis (Leydig, 1860) s. lato. F, lateral view. G, head pores. H, postabdomen. I, IDL and ODL of limb I. J – M. Alona kotovi Sinev, 2012. J, lateral view. K, head pores. L, postabdomen. M, IDL and ODL of limb I. (A – D, F – I—orig.; E—from Sinev (2009 b); J – M—from Sinev (2012 ))" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
), with parallel margins and prominent, broadly rounded distal angle, length about 4 heights. Preanal angle weakly defined, postanal angle not defined. Postanal denticles very small, in clusters. Postanal lateral groups of setulae long, in distalmost groups length of setulae exceed the width of base of postabdominal claw. Postabdominal claw long, almost straight, with short basal spine. A prominent spine located at middle of claw.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1391,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
Antennule with a single lateral aesthetasc, this and one of terminal aesthetascs much longer than others. Antennal seta without basal peg. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[648,737,1788,1813]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. A – D" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[200,1371,223,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[193,1389,223,1883]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. A – D, Acroperus africanus Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2015. A, lateral view. B, posteroventral corner of valves. C, postabdomen. D, antenna. E, Acroperus harpae (Baird, 1834), antenna. F – I, Alona affinis (Leydig, 1860) s. lato. F, lateral view. G, head pores. H, postabdomen. I, IDL and ODL of limb I. J – M. Alona kotovi Sinev, 2012. J, lateral view. K, head pores. L, postabdomen. M, IDL and ODL of limb I. (A – D, F – I—orig.; E—from Sinev (2009 b); J – M—from Sinev (2012 ))" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191533/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
–E) with thin seta on basal segment of endopodite. Spine on basal segment of exopodite about 1/34 length of middle segment. Spines on apical segments about 1/3 length of apical segments. IDL of limb I with three setae, seta 1 well-developed, seta 2–3 thin, armed with thin setulae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1391,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,410,1895,1920]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
All early records of 
<taxonomicName box="[663,779,1896,1919]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Acroperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[663,779,1896,1919]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Acroperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the region were attributed to Palearctic 
<taxonomicName class="Branchiopoda" genus="Acroperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harpae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Acroperus harpae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Korovchinsky 2013), but these populations were never studied in detail. 
<emphasis box="[1158,1172,1932,1955]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S</emphasis>
tudied specimens from North-East Thailand have morphology similar to that of recently described from Afrotropical species 
<taxonomicName authority="Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2016" authorityName="Neretina &amp; Kotov" authorityYear="2016" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Acroperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="africanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Acroperus africanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Neretina" box="[263,536,2004,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" refString="Neretina, A. N. &amp; Sinev, A. Y. (2016) A revision of the genus Leberis Smirnov, 1989 (Cladocera: Chydoridae) in the Old World and Australia. Zootaxa, 4079 (5), 501 - 533. http: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4079.5.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Neretina &amp; Kotov, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but at the moment presence of of 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1034,2004,2028]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Acroperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harpae">
<emphasis box="[924,1034,2004,2028]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">A. harpae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the region cannot be excluded.
</paragraph>
